{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_014LXcNLURcHH14dUqJK6jvc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Perfect! Now I can see the issue clearly:\n\nIn _yr_compiler_define_variable (line 857-919):\n1. At line 866-869, it looks up the variable in objects_table using `NULL` as the namespace (third parameter)\n2. At line 912-916, it adds the variable to objects_table using `NULL` as the namespace\n\nSo external variables are stored with `NULL` namespace in the objects_table.\n\nNow look at the parser.c bug (line 730-733):\n```c\nyr_hash_table_lookup(\n  compiler->objects_table,\n  identifier,\n  compiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL)\n```\n\nIt's looking up with `compiler->current_namespace->name` as the namespace, not `NULL`! This is the bug.\n\nWhen a rule tries to use the same name as an external variable, it should find it by looking it up with `NULL` as the namespace, but instead it's looking with the current namespace, so it doesn't find the conflict and doesn't return an error.\n\nThe fix is to change line 733 from `compiler->current_namespace->name` to `NULL`, which is exactly what commit cb787cc0 did.\n\nSo the ROOT CAUSE is that the fix for issue #920 was reverted or not applied in this buggy version.\n\nLet me verify this is the only issue by checking what the defects4cpp test is supposed to test. The test index should be 55, which runs test_issue_920. But wait, let me double check what test is actually running. Looking back at the test output, it said ERROR_CALLBACK_REQUIRED, but that's actually printed from test_issue_920 (with the wrong error code printed due to the printf bug).\n\nSo the test is running test_issue_920, which is testing for ERROR_DUPLICATED_IDENTIFIER when a rule has the same name as an external variable. Currently, the code is not detecting this conflict, so it's not returning ERROR_DUPLICATED_IDENTIFIER, hence the test fails.\n\n\nThe solution is straightforward: update line 733 in parser.c to use `NULL` instead of `compiler->current_namespace->name` when looking up identifiers. This ensures the lookup matches how external variables are actually stored in the objects_table, allowing the conflict detection to work properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":983,"cache_read_input_tokens":58341,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":983},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2e2d2940-6134-497c-8abb-dfacce545af5","uuid":"a0711ef2-e6a6-4530-a0bf-3089b469cdbe"}
